7sxiovcv5DSFbkE4\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class loading and metadata**\\n\\nI'm considering whether I need to add metadata for dynamic access coverage, as it may be useful for configuration. If the test uses a default factory, I wonder if the native image might fail due to reflection issues. It seems like I might need to use Class.forName for dynamic class loading. I think that if the TypeAttributeImpl is reachable via imports, I should be okay. Class.forName can load any class in the image, assuming it's registered.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing test implementation and metadata**\\n\\nI’m wondering if empty metadata might still allow existing tests to pass. I see that a static implementation uses findAttributeImplCtor for TypeAttributeImpl, but adding a default might complicate things by introducing MethodHandle without Class.forName configurations. I think I need to create a specific test class, AttributeFactoryInnerDefaultAttributeFactoryTest. To check dynamic coverage, I should use attributes not involved in other tests. Maybe I need to verify exceptions if an implementation isn’t available, which could require creating a custom public test Attribute interface.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Class.forName and test challenges**\\n\\nI'm thinking that the Class.forName call gets triggered here, but I have a test class that's a private nested type, which complicates things. The class name has a `$`, and if the implementation is absent, this directly leads to a Class.forName failure. I wonder if the dynamic access line is covered. It seems that dynamic loading of a nonexistent class in the native image should throw an IllegalArgumentException. But would this cause UnsupportedFeature issues? I’m not entirely sure.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ZQbLpQJIhYvpRFExj27Hlaul|fc_01111c4b8c2cf06a0169f4332d0900819496d0d4421096f67a", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find /h